story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. 

I grew up in Wales and have lots of happy memories spent with family in the valleys, when a friend mentioned about the DRAGON RIDE 2021, I jumped at the chance to join him and cycle around the area I grew up in for the first time on a bike.

Why am I doing it? Well my father in Law sadly died of cancer on the 14/07/2020 Roy was a true gentleman and is missed by his family every day, so I decided I am going to do a charity ride for Macmillan Cancer Support in memory of Roy.

The ride isn't going to be easy as there are a few hills to contend with

Medio Fondo














Race 

Director Difficulty rating: 8/10

Don’t let the name fool you, the “Medio” Fondo is still considerably tougher than most other sportive’s longest routes, coming in at 157km and 2111m of climbing. You’ll take on some of the most famous climbs the Dragon Ride has to offer and the sweeping scenery and quiet roads of the Brecon Beacons.

You will tackle the following major climbs:

  • Sardis Hill (3/10)
  • Glynneath Hill (6/10)
  • Bwlch Bryn-Rhudd (5/10)
  • Devils Elbow (8/10)
  • Rhigos (6/10)
  • The Bwlych (7/10)


2020 has been a strange year for all of us, but it hasn't stop us from getting out on the bike and keeping our general fitness and mental fitness in good shape, please help me to raise some money for a good cause  every donation, big or small helps with the fight against cancer.

Thank you for your support 

Chris

In Memory of Roy x

story: Welcome to my Just Giving fundraising page! I am running the 2021 Edinburgh Marathon for Macmillan Cancer Support in order to raise as much money as possible.They are a fantastic Charity and I would be so grateful if you could take the time to sponsor me to help the cause and to motivate me in my training!There are around 367,000 new cancer cases in the UK every year, that's around 1,000 every day (2015-2017). In females in the UK, there were more than 179,000 new cancer cases in 2017. In males in the UK, there were around 187,000 new cancer cases in 2017. Every two minutes someone in the UK is diagnosed with cancer.By giving to great charities such as Macmillan we can help in the fight against cancer by raising awareness and money so that a cure can be found sooner.This race will be run in memory of my Grandma, Liz, who unfortunately passed away in 2017 due to cancer.Any donation no matter big or small would mean a huge amount to me and the cause, thank you all. X

eventName: Redrow Homes Ltd MacMillan Coffee Morning
story:
This year due to Covid19 we have been unable to hold our annual coffee morning in memory of our colleagues, Angeline Jones & Karen Thomas.

This is a charity very close to our hearts and we have been raising funds for numerous years to do what we can to help the charity.

Last year we raised an eyewatering amount of money (£1341.78), and we were hoping to be able to do some fundraising raffles and cake sales to smash last years total, but with most of our colleagues working from home we didn't feel that we could host one this year, however we can still raise some money if you would like to donate online.

Fingers crossed next year we will be able to fundraise properly with cake sales, raffles and other games etc.  For now everyone needs to stay safe.


Louise & Mandy

(Legal & Accounts)

story:
At Swefn's Edge have created and produced four short audio pieces 'On The 425' with commissioned script from writer Paul Chronnell. 

Travelling on the bus, we eavesdrop as a female passenger unknowingly takes us with her on a difficult, personal journey.

One private journey within four public bus journeys.

At Swefn's Edge decided to take this opportunity to fundraise for Macmillan Cancer Support as we release 'On the 425'.

Macmillan Cancer Support helps everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, they’re right right there with you.

story:
Thank you for supporting my fundraising.

Cancer will affect someone we know, have known and will know....friends and family....it doesn’t care. So that’s why fundraising for Macmillan is important, hence the challenge!

From watching a close friend going through diagnosis, treatment and continual treatment, Macmillan have been invaluable to her and her family! She has said ‘the support they offer on all levels, from financial advice, to complimentary holistic treatments on the ward, to every member of staff that works at the Macmillan Cancer Centre...the receptionists who know me by name, the doctors who come at everything with positivity, knowing there is groundbreaking research work being done...the fact that I have just celebrated TWO years since diagnosis....not long ago, my diagnosis would have been minimal years left to live, but how research and treatment have come on so quickly, I am not only still alive, but am so confident that I have got YEARS ahead of me’.

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

eventName: Adam & Ashlie go sober for October
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone who is affected by Cancer. 

Both me and Ashlie have been affected by cancer within our families and friends in recent years and would like to give something back to one of the charities who supported us. 

After losing my Nan to cancer at Christmas and a work colleague this week, we both decided we wanted to do something to raise some money! 

As everyone knows both myself and Ashlie like a drink, so will be a tough old month but it’s something we spoke about before so thought it was the right time to do it! 


Thankyou for anything you can give to help support us! 


Adam & Ashlie x

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thank you for your support. This will give you an idea of what it means to me and more importantly to the people that will benefit from your kind donation.

I prefer to call it "our" story because it's not something I or anyone else intimately involved with went through on our own, something for which I am immensely thankful for!

It started when my father Hamish was diagnosed with prostate cancer c.2007 and underwent a multitude of treatments over many years from Brachytherapy initially followed by 2 rounds of chemotherapy and later a prostatectomy in 2018.

In Jan 2012 when things seemed to be under control with my Dad, my lovely mum Judy experienced stomach pains, was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer completely out of the blue and passed away at home with all of us by her side on 12th May, only 3 months following her diagnosis and a month before her first grandchild was born.

Throughout 2019 my Dad's health deteriorated and although his prostate cancer was known, tracked and confusingly had not worsened, he was eventually diagnosed with a far more aggressive form of small cell cancer a week before Christmas. He died on 10th January 2020 at St Columbas Hospice in Edinburgh with his closest family by his side.

You will know that our story is not unusual. We were lucky enough to have love, to have time, to have support from the NHS, from MacMillan, St Columbas, Maggies, Prostate Cancer UK, and a multitude of other charities and organisations.

Thank you for helping me battle cancer and fight back!

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

eventName: October - No cake and 30lb Weight Loss Challenge
story:
The Ramillies team have agreed to eat no cake for a month. Some staff are trying to lose 30lb between them, others are trying to be more healthy. If anyone can't resist, they have agreed to donate £1 every time they eat cake. The challenge will take place throughout October and we are trusting everyone to be honest. Those who are taking the weight loss challenge will be weighed at the start and end of October.

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge weve faced in our 60 year history. And its led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, weve never needed people like you more.

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into groundbreaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the worlds biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we cant drop the ball now.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Welcome to my fundraising page for British Heart Foundation, in honour of my Grandpa (Anthony 'Tony' Lovatt), who sadly passed away on 16th September 2020. 

My Grandpa was humble, hard working, always generous and one of a kind. He will most definitely be missed by all who knew him. 

I hope to raise some money from British Heart Foundation as they help to support 7.4 million people living with heart and circulatory diseases in the UK. Let's all help to beat heartbreak from heart and circulatory disease! 

Please feel free to donate whatever you can and I will pass on any message to my Grandma, Noreen Lovatt. Thank you to everyone in advance. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story: As some of you know my mum suffered a stroke 7 years ago. Initially she couldn't walk, speak or remember even the most basic of things. The impact on her was immense, as it was also on the family. She did make a reasonably good recovery and lived an additional 7 good years. Sadly,  this year we lost her, complications with her health related to her stroke all those years ago. So this year and future years to come, I'll be doing my dechox in her memory.  Not having chocolate for 31 days is the least I can do. The BHF has supported me in many ways over the years. It's my turn now to give them my support.  This year is particularly hard for them as people haven't been able to do fundraising as much. Please support them in any way you can, give money, give furniture or clothing to their stores, it all adds up. Thank you from the bottom of my heart 💝😘

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. I am taking part in the BHF Dechox campaign - that means no chocolate for the entire month of October!!! As a confirmed chocoholic of many years standing this will not be an easy task but BHF need the funds so other families can hopefully not have to go through what we went through. My husband Kevin died 2 years ago, very suddenly and unexpectedly from undiagnosed coronary artery disease. At only 61 he was far too young. I realise that everyone is going through a tough time at the moment, but any donation, however small would be appreciated. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.
title: Professional Photographers Supporting Guide Dogs
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
Name: Professional Photographers Supporting Guide Dogs

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Guide Dogs exists to provide life-changing services to the 360,000 people who are registered blind or partially sighted, and the two million people in the UK living with sight loss.

The Holmes Chapel and Congleton Fundraising group, is a dedicated group of supporters, including a number of blind and partially-sighted guide dog users. Some of these supporters are ‘puppy walkers’, volunteers who give up their time to bring up guide dogs from small puppies to maturity, equipping them with the skills to go into formal guide dog training prior to being ‘paired’. Some supporters provide a home for those retired guide dogs that, after several years of service, have completed their tour of duty. The group also includes supporters who may or may not have had involvement with the Guide Dogs organization, but are committed to help the organization help those who need the benefits a guide dog can bring.

We undertake a range of activities to raise funds for Guide Dogs in order to provide and support trained dogs to the visually impaired. We undertake street collections, store collections, coffee mornings and market stalls, including the Holmes Chapel Christmas Market, where we have a selection of Guide Dog branded merchandise, ideal for small gifts.

story:
One of the very first jobs I applied for was to be a guide dog puppy walker. Unfortunately I wasn't old enough or had enough experience. 

However this way I get to support Guide Dogs and the fantastic work they do. 

I have family members who have increasingly bad eyesight and would like to think that if one day they needed a guide dog, the opportunity would be there.

eventName: Laura's Els and Laura's Sober October
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

As you will know us coombs sister's love a glass of wine. To challenge ourselves and raise money for a fantastic cause we are going sober throughout the whole of October. We will not be having a single sip of alcohol so no more midweek vinos or G&Ts on the weekends. This will be a very hard challenge!

So many of our loved ones have been affected by cancer. This is why we have decided to raise money in aid of Cancer Research. The recent diagnosis of cancer to our dad has brought worry and fear into our lives. This disease affects so many. Cancer Research aims to eradicate cancer, raise awareness and help those who are suffering.

Covid has brought new difficulties for charities: 'So Far, We've Lost 44 Million Pounds of Funding into Research that Could Save Lives. We Urgently Need Your Donations to Get Back on Track and Save More Lives.' Cancer Research needs our help now more than ever.

Please donate to support us through our challenge and to help beat cancer!

Lots of Love, 

Laura and Els

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my page,

A couple of years ago my lovely Mum was diagnosed with breast cancer, which she has now beaten. Without the care of our wonderful NHS I might still not have her.  I said then that I would do some sort of charity fund raising to help in my own small way to find a cure for cancer -  unfortunately this kept getting put back! 

This year one of my sister’s best friends died of this horrible disease and I think now it’s time to stand by my word and try and make some money to get rid of it. 

I’m sure most of you know I’m awful at running, having retired from rugby a few years ago and weighing in at over 19 stone this will be a huge challenge for me! Please give something, even a little will make a huge difference.

Luckily for me I’ll be joined on the challenge by my wife, whose beloved Nanny survived cancer 60 years ago and who has been fighting another battle with it over the last few years. This means there will be 100 miles between the Birrells in October!

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I would normally walk the Race for Life earlier in the year but as this was cancelled I still wanted to do my bit and raise some much needed money for charity. story:
When someone is diagnosed with or loses a fight against cancer, it's very difficult to know what to say or do and how to cope. Not only myself, but my friends and my family have found this and unfortunately had to go through the sadness of this terrible disease as have many other people in this world and I've often felt like there's little I could do to offer support.

So... I'm hoping that by raising cash for the cause, I can do something positive and proactive to support those who have had a really tough time dealing with cancer and those who have heartbreakingly lost the fight against this cruel disease

I always thought it would be cool to cover 100K. This month is the perfect opportunity to finally do so, and I'm buzzing to be doing it. 

Any support, whether a donation or a message of encouragement, is greatly appreciated.

eventName: Grand Union Canal Autumn Half Marathon
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I spontaneously decided to run my first half marathon in one month's time. It's a great opportunity to test myself in something new, and an even better opportunity to raise money towards something I hold dear; beating cancer.

 Little over year ago I lost my Nan, Ellen, to a long-term battle with the disease. She played a huge role in bringing me up and shaping me into the person I am today.  It is in her memory and for the charitable organisation of Cancer Research UK that I will try to raise a modest sum so that I can help others going through similar hardships  that she did. 

Cancer has affected most of our families and loved ones, and I think that where possible it's important to do our loved ones proud by doing what we can to help reduce its impact on other families.

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

My dearest Wife & sole-mate Gillian Addison (Gillzy) sadly passed away on the 16th September 2020 after a short battle with cancer. 

Within just a few weeks of Gillian feeling mildly unwell the family and I found ourselves having to take full time care of Gillian as it was discovered the cancer had already spread and taken over her liver and the outlook wasn't looking good.

In the days running up to her passing, we were able to accommodate Gillian at home rather than in Hospital. Which meant she was able to be comfortable at home with family rather than in a hospital ward. 

The help we received from Marie Curie during this time was amazing. The nurses helped us every step of the way to ensure Gillian was well looked after & comfortable during her final days with us.

We asked for donations at her funeral which raised a significant amount of funds for Marie Curie. Therefore we have decided to create this just-giving page to allow more people who were not able to attend the funeral to help raise funds for the much needed charity.

Thankyou for all your help! Gillian would be blown away by the support we have all received!

story: The Covid 19 pandemic has hugely impacted the charity sector as many fundraising events have been cancelled or prevented from taking place. My daughter, Jessica is a Community Fundraiser for Marie Curie and her team are all working hard to ensure the charity still has funds for it's incredibly important work.   6 months ago, after a stress related illness, I decided to change my lifestyle and I now walk, run or swim every day, have shed 3 stone in weight and feel fitter than I have been since my 20's.  Therefore, I have decided to combine my new fitness levels with raising money for a worthy cause. Cancer touches all of our lives and at a time when our focus may be on Covid 19, we need to remember that friends, family and strangers are all suffering with various forms of this crippling disease.  If you donate even a small amount, I'd love to smash through the target of £180 - it would be great to make it £1800!

story:
Hi Everyone,

Matthew and I have decided to take part in Sober October this year to raise much-needed funds for Marie Curie Hospice in Glasgow.

As many of you will know, my Gran spent her final weeks here being cared for by the wonderful staff and this is just our way of giving something back.

The hospice in Glasgow has been helping to provide care and support since 1954. They help patients have a good quality of life, for as long as possible, and they also make sure people are comfortable in their final days, whether those days are spent in the hospice or in their own homes.

They need to raise £6,735 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. We would be so grateful for any donation, big or small! 

Love,

Siobhan xx

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last.

We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel.

We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how.

Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. 

And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 

We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Dad always supported the RNLI and sailed and used his RIB on Milford Haven - hence this money is specifically for Angle Lifeboat Station.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY

You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline  were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our countrys beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world.

Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.
title: The Big Winter Wander

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Now more than ever it’s vital the world’s poorest communities have access to clean water. Without it they cannot wash their hands to protect themselves from illness and many struggle to grow food they rely on to survive.

Although we cannot hold a large service in church this year, please help us support WaterAid by making an online donation to their Harvest Appeal.
